description: {"blocks":[{"key":"4qpcl","text":"This DNA extraction method for Schistosoma mansoni cercariae is based on the HOTSHOT method https://health.uconn.edu/mouse-genome-modification/protocols/hotshot-method-of-dna-preparation/. DNA isolation is followed by PCR amplification of the \"W1\" female W chromosome repetitive region. The 476 bp W1 repeat was identified by Webster, Mansour, and Bieber (1989). PCR primers for the W1 repeat were designed by Gasser, Morahan, and Mitchell (1991). steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"7l4ud","text":"While holding with wide-tip featherweight forceps, rinse patent Biomphalaria glabrata snails, individually, with MilliQ water","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":64,"length":21}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6g46k","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3979b","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"s633","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"areh7","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"6v935","text":"- Rinsing snails individually prevents cross-contamination of cercariae from another snail","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"94vi1","text":"- Snails should be at least 5 weeks post infection with a single miracidium ","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"36mpl","text":"Place rinsed snails into individual wells of  6- or 12-well plates","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"6llml","text":"Add 3-4ml of MilliQ water to each well","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"16pbq","text":"Induce shedding of cercariae by place snails under a direct light for up to 2 hours or until cercariae are visible in well with a naked eye","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5agrd","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2ceii","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"addfk","text":"After 2 hrs, remove snails that are not shedding cercariae and place into a new tank with food. These snails can be re-shed in one week. Some monomiracidium-infected snails will not begin shedding until up to 8 weeks after exposure. At this time, if they are still not shedding cercariae, it is safe to assume they were not infected and can be disposed of properly. {"blocks":[{"key":"61ikb","text":"For snails that are shedding low amounts of cercariae (\u003c100), place into a new tank with food and re-shed in one week","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"989q7","text":"Put an \"X\" on the wells of the snails that are shedding and uniquely number each. This numbering must be preserved throughout. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
